This repository contains my hands-on Linux lab environment created using Oracle VM VirtualBox for practicing real-world system administration and networking concepts. The lab is built on a local virtualization setup using Linux Mint as the host operating system, while multiple Ubuntu virtual machines are configured as Linux server and client systems for testing and administration tasks.
In this project, I created and configured multiple Ubuntu virtual machines with manual IP addressing, SSH connectivity, and secure remote access between systems. The lab environment is designed to simulate a real production infrastructure where server-client communication, storage management, and network services can be tested practically. I also configured NFS file sharing for centralized storage access and implemented LVM (Logical Volume Management) to manage flexible disk partitions and storage allocation.
The repository demonstrates practical Linux administration skills including user and permission management, package installation, service management, network configuration, file sharing, remote access setup, and virtualization management. It also includes basic troubleshooting, system monitoring, and command-line operations commonly used by Linux and system administrators in enterprise environments.
This lab project helped me gain hands-on experience with Linux server management, virtualization concepts, networking fundamentals, and infrastructure configuration in a controlled learning environment. The repository will continue to be updated with additional Linux administration tasks, automation scripts, monitoring tools, and server management practices as I expand my learning journey in Linux and cloud technologies.
